> You HAVE to decide what you&#x27;re going to do in case of an error.<p>This is not true in all cases:<p><pre><code>    func f() error { ... }

    func main() {
        f() // OK
        fmt.Println(&quot;Uh-oh&quot;)
    }</code></pre>

Yet,  in c# if you do<p><pre><code>  int foo(obBob o) { o.x += 1; return o; }
  ...
  Car.x = 3;
  foo(Car);
</code></pre>
Then Car.x = 4 which has confused a lot of new programmers. More importantly it&#x27;s a more consice standard for cube(x) to cube(x) than to say x=cube(x).
